==Stay safe== *{{listing | name=Malmi Health Station | alt=Malmin terveysasema | url=https://www.hel.fi/en/health-and-social-services/health-care/health-stations/malmi-health-station | email= | address=Talvelantie 4 | lat=60.2542 | long=25.0015 | directions=in the Ylä-Malmi district | phone=+358 93 105 7702 | tollfree= | fax= | hours=M-F 08:00-18:00 | price= | content=Sub-divisional health centre. }}
In emergencies, {{phone|112 (free from all phones)}}. This includes social services, although for non-urgent matters you could contact the social services directly.
==Go next== * [[Helsinki/Eastern suburbs|Helsinki's eastern suburbs]] * [[Vantaa]]
{{IsPartOf|Helsinki}} {{usabledistrict}}
{{geo|60.239|24.935}}

{{pagebanner|pgname=Southern Helsinki|WV banner Helsinki South Eira street.jpg|unesco=yes}}
'''South Helsinki''' is in this guide defined as the part of [[Helsinki]] south of the Esplanadi and Bulevardi streets. It also includes the archipelago south of Helsinki, such as the Suomenlinna islands.
The southernmost part of the Helsinki peninsula, this is a calm part of Helsinki with the city's most affluent residential areas (especially in the Eira district), probably more than half of the embassies and consulates in Helsinki and lots of greenery including the Observatory Hill and Kaivopuisto. If you're interested in upscale fashion, design shopping and trendy cafés, this is where you should head in Helsinki. On the other hand, the western corner of this district has a more industrial character, with the shipyard, warehouses and the famous Kahvila Suomi serving traditional Finnish food for workers in the marine industries for decades.
Beyond the coastline, lined by yachts in the summer, there are several small islands that have something to offer to visitors, from outdoor activities to exclusive eateries. By far the largest, best known and most popular is Suomenlinna — actually a cluster of four islands connected by bridges. This former fortification is inscribed on the [[UNESCO World Heritage List]], but it's not just a tourist attraction. It is also home to several hundred inhabitants.
==Get in== {{mapframe|60.15273|24.95203|zoom=12|layer=W}}
From the central railway station, bus station or central Helsinki in general, there isn't anywhere in southern Helsinki you couldn't get on foot within half an hour or so. Out of public transport modes, tram (1, 3, 6 and 10) are probably your best bet, though there are some bus lines (14, 18) too. If you wish to go to Suomenlinna, board the ferry from the Market square.
For yachts, customs clearing (if needed) is handled at the coast guard station; phone +358 295-426-310. There are guest harbours at [http://www.valimo.org/vierassatama/ Suomenlinna]{{Dead link|date=January 2023 |bot=InternetArchiveBot }} and Pihlajasaari.
==Get around== If you aren't going by foot or bike, tram is the best alternative; line 3 takes you around southern Helsinki.
To get to Suomenlinna, take the {{marker|type=go|name=HSL ferry|url=https://www.suomenlinna.fi/en/visitor/how-to-get-there/hsl-ferry/|lat=60.16739|long=24.95563}} from the Market Square.
==See== [[File:Johannes Church Helsinki.jpg|thumbnail|St.John's, one of the most impressive churches in Helsinki]]
* {{see | name=Observatory Hill | alt=Tähtitornin vuori | url=http://www.ursa.fi/english.html | email= | address= | lat=60.161901 | long=24.951673 | directions= | phone= | tollfree= | fax= | hours= | price= | content=As the name reveals, this hill rising above the Olympia and Makasiini terminals of South Harbor hosts an observatory, and from the hill you have a nice albeit partial view over the city centre (part of the view is obstructed by trees). It is also the place for people to picnic on the may day festival Vappu and on the morning of the Finnish Independence Day the hill hosts a televised flag rising ceremony. }} ** {{see | name=Ursa Observatory | alt=Ursan tähtitorni | url=https://www.ursa.fi/palvelut/tahtitornit/kaivopuiston-tahtitorni.html| email= | address=Ehrenströmintie 1, [[Helsinki]], [[Finland]] | lat=60.155495 | long=24.955445 | directions=at the [[Kaivopuisto|Kaivopuisto park]] | phone=+358 9 6840-4080 | tollfree= | fax= | hours=Open occationally | price=€5 for adults, €2 for under age of 16; free for members | wikipedia=Ursa Observatory | wikidata=Q7901150 | content=The 1926 yellow-coloured observatory, operated by the Astronomical Association Ursa, is still in active use by both members and other enthusiasts, but non-members can also attend public shows to either observe solar phenomena or look at the starry sky. }} * {{see | name=Diana Park | alt=Diananpuisto | url= | email= | address= | lat=60.16503 | long=24.94354 | directions= | phone= | tollfree= | fax= | hours= | price= | content=Also known as Kolmikulma (the triangle), this pocket sized park is a nice place to take break from your sightseeing in the summer and just sit down on a park bench and have an ice-cream. }} * {{see | name=Kaivopuisto | alt= | url= | email= | address= | lat=60.156816 | long=24.956790 | directions= | phone= | tollfree= | fax= | hours= | price= | content=A beautiful park by the sea in the southernmost part of the city. In summer you might want to sit down for a cup of coffee in one of the seaside cafes and enjoy the view of sailboats and the people on the promenade. Housing surrounding this area is the most expensive in Helsinki. }} * {{see | name=Sinebrychoffin puisto | alt= | url= | email= | address= | lat=60.161618 | long=24.933646 | directions= | phone= | tollfree= | fax= | hours= | price= | content=Also known as "Koffin puisto", it's in Punavuori district next to the Sinebrychoff art museum. Popular with young people, in the summer it is full of people having picnics or just drinking ''pussikalja'' (literally: "beer in a bag", means buying beer from a supermarket and drinking it outdoors), while in the winter kids ride sleds down the snowy slope. }} * {{see | name=St. John's Church | alt=Johanneksenkirkko | url= | email= | address=Korkeavuorenkatu 12 | lat=60.1618 | long=24.9450 | directions= | image=Johannes Church Helsinki.jpg | phone=+358 9 7092370 | tollfree= | fax= | hours=M-F 12:00-15:00 | price=Free. | content=The largest church in Helsinki and a fine example of Gothic Revival architecture. }} * {{see | name=German Church | alt=Saksalainen kirkko | url=http://www.deutschegemeinde.fi/en/ | email= | address=Bernhardinkatu 4 | lat=60.1633 | long=24.9520 | directions= | phone= | tollfree= | fax= | hours= | price= | content=The Lutheran Church of the German community is situated at the foot of the Observatory Hill and is a visible landmark if you are walking from the Silja Line ferry towards downtown. The Neo-Gothic church was built in 1864 and is also a venue for liturgical and classical concerts. }} * {{see | name=Mikael Agricola Church | alt= | url= | email= | address=Tehtaankatu 23 | lat=60.15835 | long=24.93898 | directions= | phone= | tollfree= | fax= | hours= | price= | content=A prime example of 1930s [[Functionalist architecture in Finland|functionalism]] at the border of districts of Eira and Punavuori. Slightly unusually for this architectural style it's constructed in red bricks. The spire of the church can be lowered into the church tower, a feature that was used during WWII to make it less visible for Soviet bombers. }}<!-- -->[[File:Mannerheim Museum.jpg|thumbnail|Mannerheim museum]] * {{see | name=Mannerheim Museum | alt= | url=http://www.mannerheim-museo.fi/ | email= | address=Kalliolinnantie 14 | lat=60.158789 | long=24.960458 | directions=Trams 1A and 2 | phone= | tollfree= | hours=F-Su 11:00-16:00 | price=€8 | content=Finnish Marshall Carl Gustav Emil Mannerheim lived in this villa 1924—51. The museum contains his personal home and a vast array of items he acquired during his life and on his long journeys. }} * {{see | name=Newspaper museum | alt=Päivälehden museo | url=http://www.paivalehdenmuseo.fi/en/museum/ | email= | address=Ludviginkatu 2-4 | lat=60.165585 | long=24.944264 | directions= | phone= | tollfree= | fax= | hours=Tu-Su 11:00-17:00 | price=Free | content=In the newspaper museum you can learn more about the history of newspapers - journalism and printing. }} * {{see | name=Sinebrychoff Museum | alt= | url=https://sinebrychoffintaidemuseo.fi/en/ | email= | address=Bulevardi 40 | lat=60.16257 | long=24.93255 | directions= | phone= | tollfree= | hours=Tu, F 10:00–18:00, W, Th 10:00–20:00, Sa-Su 10:00–17:00 | price=€20 for the whole collection, free entry for house museum and permanent exhibition only | content=Promotes itself as the only museum in Finland specializing in old European art. Located in a stately house commissioned in 1842 by Nikolai Sinebrychoff, the founder of the Sinebrychoff brewery. Nikolai Sinebrychoff never lived in the house, preferring instead to live in Viapori (now known as Suomenlinna), but his brother's family lived there for several years. The upper floor of the building hosts the Sinebrychoff house museum with plenty of 19th-century paintings on display. }} * {{see | name=Design Museum | url=http://www.designmuseum.fi/en/ | email= | address=Korkeavuorenkatu 23 | lat=60.162844 | long=24.945513 | directions= | phone=+358 9 622 0540 | tollfree= | fax= | hours=Tu 11:00-20:00, W-Su 11:00-18:00. Closed Mondays. | price=Admission €10 | content=Exhibitions of modern commercial and industrial design and modern art. The permanent exhibit in the basement showcases the history of consumer-goods design over the course of the 20th century, with a particular focus on the contributions of Finnish designers. If you're a fan of Finnish design products like Marimekko fabrics, Arabia porcelain and Iittala vases and their prototypes this is definitely not a place to miss. }} * {{see | name=Pihlajasaari | alt= | url=https://www.hel.fi/helsinki/en/culture/recreation/islands/pihlajasaari | email= | address= | lat=60.1375 | long=24.917778| directions= | phone= | tollfree= | fax= | hours=| price= | wikidata=Q24318062 | content=Few tourists find their way here, but this is a very popular summer spot for Helsinkians, with sandy beaches (including a mixed nude beach) and a restaurant dishing out cold beer and ciders. Ferries run from Merisatama pier at the southern end of Kaivopuisto Park (tram 3) hourly from 09:30 to 20:30, 10-15 min, €5.50 return. }}
===Suomenlinna=== [[File:Suomenlinna.jpg|thumb|300px|Suomenlinna fortress, seen from a passing ferry]]
If you see only one place in Helsinki in the summer, make it {{Marker|type=see|name=Suomenlinna |lat=60.1454 | long=24.9893 |url=https://www.suomenlinna.fi/en/}} (Swedish: ''Sveaborg''). The "Gibraltar of the North" was once the greatest sea fortress in the Baltic, built by the Swedish in the mid-1700s at great expense to protect their eastern flank. But when the Russians invaded in February 1808, the bulk of the unprepared and bankrupt Swedish army hastily withdrew, allowing the Russians to conquer Helsinki without a fight and besiege the fortress. With no reinforcements in sight, commander Carl Olof Cronstedt surrendered unconditionally two months later, and Finland was ceded to the Russians. Cronstedt's actions probably saved countless civilian lives, but King Gustav IV needed a scapegoat and sentenced him to death for treason; fortunately, the losing king was himself soon overthrown, and Cronstedt lived out his years gardening.
Today's Suomenlinna is still living in its own time with only old buildings, few cars, fewer than a thousand inhabitants and lots of old fortifications, catacombs and cast iron cannons. But it's not just a museum: the sprawling complex houses restaurants, cafés, theatres and museums, and is a very popular place for a picnic on a fine summer day, watching the vast passenger ferries drift by on their way to Estonia and St Petersburg. It was included in UNESCO’s [[World Heritage List]] in 1991 as a unique monument to European military architecture.
Entry to the island itself is free, but you need to pay for the ferry ride. The HSL ferry from Market Square is the cheapest and most convenient way of getting there at €9 for a 12-hour tourist return. The ferry is a part of the Helsinki local traffic, so if you have an HSL Day Ticket it includes ferry travel. The ferry runs approximately every half hour. On summer weekends the island is a popular picnic destination and you may have to wait for a long time as hundreds of people crowd the ferry terminal. In this case it may be worth it to use the more expensive private ferry company at the other end of the Market Square.
Guided tours of the island in English are available daily at 11:00 and 14:00 in Jun-Aug, and on Sa Su only at 13:30 the rest of the year, €7/person, and history buffs will want to drop into the '''[https://www.suomenlinna.fi/en/visitor/museums/suomenlinna-museum/ Suomenlinna Museum]{{Dead link|date=May 2025 |bot=InternetArchiveBot }}''' at the Visitor Centre (€6.50).
[[File:Submarine Vesikko, Helsinki, East view 20100825 1.jpg|thumbnail|Submarine Vesikko]]
* {{see | name=Ehrensvärd Museum | alt=Ehrensvärd-museo | url=https://www.suomenlinna.fi/en/visitor/museums/ehrensvard-museum/ | email= | address=Suomenlinna B 40 | lat=60.1442 | long=24.9856 | directions= | phone=+358 9 68999850 | tollfree= | hours= | price=Adults €5, children €2 | wikidata=Q11856942 | content==The first occupant of the current museum building was Augustin Ehrensvärd (1710-1772), the founder of the Suomenlinna fortress. The museum's collection includes paintings, furniture, weapons and ship models. }} * {{see | name=Military Museum Manege | alt=Sotamuseon maneesi | url=https://sotamuseo.fi/en/frontpage | email= | address=Suomenlinna, Iso Mustasaari | lat=60.1458 | long=24.9895 | directions=Take an inexpensive ferry from Kauppatori | phone= | tollfree= | hours=Summer opening 12 May-31 Aug (but closed 19-21 Jun) daily 11:00-18:00 | price=€5 | wikidata=Q283140 | content==Founded in 1929, the central museum of the Finnish Defence Forces. Exhibits vehicles and armament used by Finnish forces during the Winter War and World War II. }} * {{see | name=Submarine Vesikko | alt= | url=http://www.mpkk.fi/en/museum/exhibitions/suomenlinnaisland.html | email= | address=Suomenlinna, Susisaari | lat=60.1424 | long=24.9896 | directions=Take an inexpensive ferry from Kauppatori | phone= | tollfree= | hours=Summer opening 12 May-31 Aug (but closed 19-21 Jun) daily 11:00-18:00 | price=€5 | content=Vesikko was one of five submarines to serve the Finnish Navy during the wars in 1939–1944. It´s also the only surviving German Type II submarine in the world (Vesikko was the prototype). }} * {{see | name=Toy Museum | alt= | url=http://lelumuseo.fi/toymuseum/ | email= | address= | lat=60.145847 | long=24.991456 | directions=east side of Suomenlinna, follow signposts from the main path | phone= | tollfree= | fax= | hours=11:00-17:00 | price=€6 | lastedit=2017-09-27 | content=Lovely old house with a dense collection of toys, notable for the wealth of information provided about the historical toys. The house includes the excellent Cafe Samovarbar. }}
==Do== * {{do | name=Beach of Uunisaari | alt= | url=http://www.uunisaari.com/en/ {{dead link|December 2020}} | email= | address=Uunisaari island | lat=60.15273 | long=24.95203 | directions= | phone= | tollfree= | fax= | hours= | price= | content=One of the better kept secrets of Helsinki is the beach on Uunisaari, an island a short ride away from the south coast. }} * {{do | name=Jääherne | alt= | url=http://www.helsinginjaahalli.fi/fin/index.php/jaavuorot/hernesaaren-jaahalli {{dead link|December 2020}} | email= | address=Hernematalankatu 6 | lat=60.14915 | long=24.92141 | directions= | phone= | tollfree= | fax= | hours= | price= | content=Try some ice hockey with your friends in the Jääherne ice hall on the southwesternmost tip of Helsinki. }} * {{do | name=Seapoint | alt= | url=https://seapoint.fi/fi_FI/seapoint-palvelut-2/vuokraveneet/liuskaluoto | email= | address=Liuskaluoto | lat=60.153012 | long=24.944442 | directions= | phone= | tollfree= | hours= | price= | lastedit=2023-05-16 | content=Motorboat rental in Merisatama. }}
